#import "@local/elektroedde:0.1.0": *
#show: problem

=
In one sentence, justify *Earnshaw's Theorem*: A charged particle cannot be held in a stable equilibrium by electrostatic forces alone. As an example, consider the cubical arrangement of fixed charges in Fig. 3.4. It looks, off hand, as though a positive charge at the center would be suspended in midair, since it
is repelled away from each corner. Where is the leak in this “electrostatic bottle”?
[To harness nuclear fusion as a practical energy source it is necessary to heat a plasma (soup of charged particles) to fantastic temperatures—so hot that contact
would vaporize any ordinary pot. Earnshaw's theorem says that electrostatic containment is also out of the question. Fortunately, it is possible to confine a hot plasma magnetically.]

#solution[
  There is no local maximum or minimum point in the solution to Laplace's equation. The apparent equilibrium point in the example must therefore be a saddle point.
]